		</div>
		
		
		
		<hr class="show-hr1">	
		
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1 show-map" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/54/Hungary_in_Europe.svg">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Hungary is a land locked country in Central Europe. The territory was inhabited by many peoples and empire including the Celts, Romans, Germanic tribes, Huns and the West Slavs. In 895 Magyars came to the land, and these people would be the ancestors of the Hungarians. In 1000 AD the Kingdom of Hungary was created. It was a Christian Kingdom and between the 12 and 15th centuries it was a cultural and a political power.
			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img2" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d2/Feszty_vezerek.jpg/1200px-Feszty_vezerek.jpg">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
					<em><figcaption>The Magyars are the ancestors of Hungariens</figcaption></em>
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				By the end of the 15th century Hungary was occupied by the Ottoman Empire and stayed under their control until the Habsburg rule took over the land in the 18th century, later becoming a part of the Austro-Hungarian Empire. With Austro-Hungarian Empire collapse after World War I, Hungary lost 70% of its territory and people. Hungary joined the Axis powers in World War II and after their defeat became a satellite state for the
Soviet Union. After the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1989 Hungary became a democratic parliamentary republic.

			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Today Hungary is a part of the European Union, United Nations and the Schengen Area. It has a high income economy, and provides its citizens social security system, universal health care and free university education system.
			</p>
		</div>

		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Geographically Hungary is on mostly flat rolling hills. Climate of Hungary is mostly cold cloudy winters and warm summers.

			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/9e/Balaton_Hungary_Landscape.jpg">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
					<em><figcaption>Lake Balaton in western Hungary</figcaption></em>
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Hungary has several thermal caves and over 1000 thermal springs attracting many tourists every year. Lake Hévíz is the largest natural thermal lake in Europe. Lake Balaton in the Transdanubian region of Hungary is the largest fresh water lake in Central Europe. The capital city Budapest is situated on the banks of the Danube, the broad river that threads through Central Europe.

			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1" src="https://ee24.com/media/articles/uploads/2013/12/19/heviz-lake.jpg">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
					<em><figcaption>Natural thermal lakek Hévíz in Hungary</figcaption></em>
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				The people of Hungary call themselves Magyars, not Hungarians. Their language is actually called Magyar. Magyar has no words that correlates to “son” or “daughter”, but has many different words for different types of cousins!

			</p>
		</div>
	
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<h3 class="show-factsh3">
				Two unique facts about Hungary
			</h3>
		</div>
			
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Attila the Hun was a ruthless warrior, and a barbaric ruler of the Huns from 434 to 453. During his reign he was one of the most feared enemies of the Roman Empire. He was said to have died in his sleep choking on his own blood during a nose bleed. However, there are no clear accounts of this, so nobody knowns how he really died. He was 46 years old.


			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1" src="https://i.natgeofe.com/n/ef679a62-2333-45c5-8ba5-cfbfde33c094/01-huns-mmxcxm_16x9.jpg?w=1200">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
					<em><figcaption>Attila the Hun</figcaption></em>
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				The Labyrinth under the Buda Castle in Budapest is a big tourist spot. The creepy cave system was once a prison and torture chamber in the 16th century. It was also a Harem and a Hospital for wounded during World War II.
			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		
		
		
		
		
